{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Reviewer dispatch sends the same source document and correct reviewer-specific instruction pack to each reviewer role.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between dispatcher and three reviewer adapters (MOCK-MISS). This can be caught by wiring real dispatch code to in-process test doubles and asserting per-role payloads. Rejected System because behavior text is about argument routing, not real network/OS/subprocess behavior (REJECTION-GATE: \"sends ... correct reviewer-specific instruction pack\"). Rejected Agentic/Workflow because no claim depends on model judgment quality.","test_description":"Run dispatcher with one contract and three in-process reviewer stubs; assert each stub receives the exact same document bytes and the correct role-specific instruction pack, including no cross-role mixups under parallel dispatch.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.04,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The live clause extractor identifies key terms (parties, dates, obligations, penalties) present in the contract.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Correctness depends on real model extraction quality (LLM-DEP, AI-CALL-DEFAULT). A stubbed extractor would always return expected keys and hide real misses on phrasing/format variation (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected Workflow because this behavior targets one reviewer’s decision, not multi-step agent pipeline sequencing (REJECTION-GATE: \"live clause extractor identifies key terms\").","test_description":"Call the real clause extractor on representative contracts and assert required key-term categories are found with acceptable recall/precision thresholds across multiple runs/doc variants.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.82,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Risk-policy configuration is passed correctly to the risk assessor invocation.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is invocation plumbing correctness across modules, not model output quality. In-process stubs can validate the exact policy payload and version forwarded. Rejected Agentic because behavior text is only about passing config, not whether assessment quality changes (REJECTION-GATE: \"configuration is passed correctly\"). Rejected System because no real OS/network semantics are required.","test_description":"Execute risk-assessor call path with a known policy object and a stub assessor endpoint; assert serialized payload contains the expected policy fields, values, and version, including edge cases (empty optional rules, overrides).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.78,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The live risk assessor flags language that is problematic under policy, including indirect or euphemistic phrasing.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on semantic judgment of problematic/indirect phrasing, which is model-output dependent (LLM-DEP, AI-CALL-DEFAULT). Mock outputs would mask real false negatives/positives (MOCK-HIDE). Rejected Workflow because only one reviewer’s judgment is under test (REJECTION-GATE: \"live risk assessor flags language ...\").","test_description":"Invoke the real risk assessor with policy and contracts containing direct and euphemistic risky clauses; assert expected risky spans are flagged with acceptable quality thresholds and document known variance bands.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.84,"Workflow":0.06}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Jurisdiction and regulatory profile are passed correctly to the compliance checker invocation.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure mode is cross-module parameter handoff (dispatcher/config layer -> compliance adapter). Deterministic stubs are sufficient to catch wrong or missing jurisdiction/profile fields. Rejected Agentic because behavior does not test compliance decision quality, only invocation inputs (REJECTION-GATE: \"are passed correctly ... invocation\").","test_description":"Run compliance invocation path with test jurisdiction/profile matrices and a stub checker; assert outgoing request contains exact jurisdiction code, regulatory profile IDs, and precedence rules.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.14,"Integration":0.79,"System":0.04,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"The live compliance checker correctly determines whether the contract meets all configured regulatory requirements.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This is model decision correctness against regulatory requirements, not just transport/routing (LLM-DEP, AI-CALL-DEFAULT). Stubbed responses cannot reveal real reasoning/classification failures. Rejected Workflow because this behavior isolates one reviewer’s determination rather than multi-agent handoff chain (REJECTION-GATE: \"live compliance checker correctly determines\").","test_description":"Evaluate the real compliance checker on a labeled contract set per jurisdiction/profile, asserting pass/fail decisions and key requirement-level findings meet agreed quality thresholds.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.09}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When two reviewers flag the same clause with conflicting assessments (for example extractor says `standard` but risk assessor says `high risk`), the merge step preserves both assessments with attribution.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at module boundary where heterogeneous reviewer outputs are normalized/merged (MOCK-MISS). A pure unit test of merge logic may miss schema/adaptor mismatches; wiring real output mappers plus merge catches that. Rejected Agentic/Workflow because behavior concerns conflict preservation logic, not model judgment quality (REJECTION-GATE: \"merge step preserves both assessments with attribution\").","test_description":"Feed merge pipeline with realistic reviewer-output objects from extractor and risk adapters containing same-clause conflicting labels; assert unified report keeps both assessments, source attribution, and no overwrite.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.33,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":8,"description":"End-to-end orchestration (dispatch all three reviewers, collect outputs, merge unified report) succeeds on a real contract without losing any reviewer findings.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"This chains multiple real agentic reviewer calls plus orchestration/merge, so correctness depends on multi-step agentic handoff (MULTI-STEP + AI-CALL-DEFAULT). Lower levels can verify plumbing but can miss losses caused by interaction between parallel live outputs and downstream merge. Rejected Agentic-only because behavior explicitly covers full sequence \"dispatch ... collect ... merge\" across three reviewers.","test_description":"Run full pipeline on real contracts using live extractor, risk assessor, and compliance checker in parallel; verify final unified report contains every reviewer finding (with attribution) and no dropped items across repeated runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.16,"Workflow":0.76}}]}
